The '''south coast tornado''' was a [[tornado|tornadic]] [[waterspout]] spawned by a [[supercell|supercell thunderstorm]] off the south coast of [[New South Wales]] on 26 December 2001, during the [[Sydney to Hobart Yacht Race]]. The tornado passed very close to the [[yacht]] ''[[Nicorette II]]'', which was severely damaged but able to complete the race with a spare [[mainsail]]. ''Nicorette'' recorded [[wind speed]]s of close to {{convert|100|kn|mph km/h m/s}} (making the tornado at least F2 on the [[Fujita scale]]) and was struck by [[hail]] the size of [[golf ball]]s. According to the boat's [[meteorology|meteorologist]], the tornado began with a diameter of around {{convert|50|m|ft|abbr=off|sp=us}}, but grew in size until it was {{convert|500|m|ft|abbr=off|sp=us}} across.<ref>http://www.weatherzone.com.au/cgi-bin/ultimatebb.cgi?ubb=get_topic;f=5;t=000166</ref> The waterspout proceeded to strike several other boats with weaker winds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.cnn.com/2001/WORLD/sailing/12/27/sydney.spt/index.html|title=CNN - Breaking News, Latest News and Videos|publisher=|accessdate=1 March 2017}}</ref> The tornado should not be confused with the severe storm that wrought havoc on the [[1998 Sydney to Hobart Yacht Race#1998 Sydney to Hobart Yacht Race Tragedy|race in 1998]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rolexsydneyhobart.com/editorial.asp?key=551 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-03-24 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040305140852/http://rolexsydneyhobart.com/editorial.asp?key=551 |archivedate=2004-03-05 |df= }}</ref>
